WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:00.752
pretty interesting.

00:01.332 --> 00:05.916
And they also do these studies on this special ImageNet dataset.

00:05.976 --> 00:10.180
For example, ImageNet C, you can see that there are quite a bit of distortions right here.

00:10.260 --> 00:13.823
I don't even see if you can see it on this video, but this is a swing.

00:13.883 --> 00:21.711
So the swing right here is like something like this, but you almost can't see it.

00:22.171 --> 00:30.038
And you see that the bold on the left is always the prediction of their model, while the thing on the right is the prediction of the original model.

00:30.018 --> 00:45.040
So this model they claim is significantly more robust to these kinds of perturbations, and they do an analysis of this where they show, yes, in fact, it is.

00:45.020 --> 00:56.400
So I think we've already seen this at the beginning that the noisy student is significantly more robust to these perturbations and they also test this to adversarial perturbations.

00:56.840 --> 01:02.831
So right here you can see that the original model drops pretty quickly as you increase the epsilon.

01:02.851 --> 01:06.437
The epsilon is kind of the strength of the adversarial perturbation.

01:06.417 --> 01:19.178
And the original model drops very quickly to fairly low accuracy, while as the noisy student training drops much, much less quickly.

01:19.462 --> 01:30.017
Now, this is another testament to the fact that what you do, I think what's happening is you have your data space, right?

01:30.037 --> 01:31.960
And you have your data points in it.

01:32.701 --> 01:44.578
Now, when you do the like normal data augmentation, what you'll do is you not only force the model to predict those points correctly, but you'll sort of make a bit of a cloud around them.

01:44.838 --> 01:48.844
And you force the model to predict that cloud correctly.

01:49.246 --> 01:59.679
Now, if you introduce more data and you do even more noise, what you do is you'll make these clouds kind of larger.

01:59.719 --> 02:05.706
And that means the model is more robust to any sort of perturbations in these clouds, right?

02:06.166 --> 02:11.693
And that means it's probably also going to be more robust to adversarial perturbations.

02:11.673 --> 02:17.944
So that's sort of how you can think of this introduction of noise to make it more generalizable.

02:18.205 --> 02:19.607
How does this generalize better?

02:19.988 --> 02:28.163
So if you think of this data point right here, if I'm looking to generalize, that means I have this IID data set.

02:28.143 --> 02:32.632
Probably my test data is going to be related to the training data.

02:32.652 --> 02:41.028
So I might get a data point that's fairly close to that data point and generalizing means I classified correctly.

02:41.368 --> 02:46.438
Now, if this cloud is very small, like it is here, my decision boundary could be like

02:46.418 --> 02:47.640
here, right?

02:48.521 --> 02:58.075
And even though the test data set is fairly close to the original training data point, it won't be classified incorrectly.

02:58.295 --> 03:11.734
However, if my original cloud during training is larger, you can see if I train a model, it can maybe put the decision boundary here, and then my test data point will be included in on that same side.

03:11.714 --> 03:14.439
So that's kind of the idea behind generalizing better.

03:14.479 --> 03:16.983
Of course, that's a vast simplification.

03:17.444 --> 03:21.110
And also to say that this here is an FGSM attack.

03:21.130 --> 03:26.599
So this is kind of the weakest attack in the adversarial perturbation spectrum.

03:27.080 --> 03:36.135
They do say under a stronger attack, PGD, which is a fairly strong attack with 10 iterations at epsilon equals 16,

03:36.115 --> 03:41.382
noisy student training improves efficient netl2's accuracy from 1.1% to 4.4% like this.

03:41.402 --> 03:51.495
1.1% really means the model is almost dead.

03:51.535 --> 03:55.660
This is like random performance.

03:55.640 --> 04:08.614
And 4.4% is still a bit above random performance, but you could probably get there by simply using any sort of noise in that case.

04:09.476 --> 04:20.044
But still, you can see that it is more robust, especially to natural distortions, and therefore it generalizes better.

